00:58:20,744 --> 00:58:22,829
Put it, put it down.

765
00:58:31,588 --> 00:58:33,588
Take it easy.

766
00:58:33,757 --> 00:58:35,757
You'll be all right.

767
00:58:36,384 --> 00:58:38,078
Him? What about me?

768
00:58:38,178 --> 00:58:40,664
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat!

769
00:58:40,764 --> 00:58:42,791
You've had worse from shaving.

770
00:58:42,891 --> 00:58:45,085
What did you do to set him off?

771
00:58:45,185 --> 00:58:47,921
Nothing.
I come in here to say farewell.

772
00:58:48,021 --> 00:58:51,591
Ain't you heard?
His parole's come through.

773
00:58:53,026 --> 00:58:55,929
I just don't understand
what happened in there.

774
00:58:56,029 --> 00:58:58,932
Old man's crazy as a rat in a tin shithouse.

775
00:58:59,032 --> 00:59:01,017
That's enough out of you.

776
00:59:01,117 --> 00:59:04,020
- Heard he had you shitting your pants.
- Fuck you.

777
00:59:04,120 --> 00:59:06,120
Knock it off.

778
00:59:06,289 --> 00:59:08,289
Brooks ain't no bug.

779
00:59:11,586 --> 00:59:13,966
He's just institutionalized.

780
00:59:14,714 --> 00:59:16,742
"Institutionalized," my ass.

781
00:59:16,842 --> 00:59:20,954
The man's been in here 50 years,
Heywood, 50 years!

782
00:59:21,054 --> 00:59:22,873
This is all he knows.

783
00:59:22,973 --> 00:59:25,375
In here, he's an important man...

784
00:59:25,475 --> 00:59:27,294
...an educated man.

785
00:59:27,394 --> 00:59:29,394
Outside, he's nothing.

786
00:59:30,188 --> 00:59:33,800
Just a used-up con
with arthritis in both hands.

787
00:59:33,900 --> 00:59:37,053
Probably couldn't get a library card
if he tried.

788
00:59:37,153 --> 00:59:39,055
You know what I'm trying to say?

789
00:59:39,155 --> 00:59:42,895
I do believe you're talking out of your ass.

790
00:59:43,326 --> 00:59:45,876
You believe whatever you want.

791
00:59:46,162 --> 00:59:49,307
But I tell you these walls are funny.

792
00:59:50,166 --> 00:59:52,166
First you hate them.

793
00:59:53,670 --> 00:59:55,880
Then you get used to them.

794
00:59:57,507 --> 00:59:59,509
Enough time passes...

795
01:00:00,177 --> 01:00:02,982
...you get so you depend on them.

796
01:00:03,180 --> 01:00:05,475
That's "institutionalized. "

797
01:00:05,599 --> 01:00:07,000
Shit.

798
01:00:07,100 --> 01:00:10,415
- I could never get like that.
- Oh, yeah?

799
01:00:10,729 --> 01:00:13,381
Wait till you've been here
as long as Brooks.

800
01:00:13,481 --> 01:00:15,481
Goddamn right.

801
01:00:17,611 --> 01:00:20,161
They send you here for life...

802
01:00:20,197 --> 01:00:23,002
...that's exactly what they take.

803
01:00:24,284 --> 01:00:26,409
Part that counts, anyway.

804
01:00:33,877 --> 01:00:37,192
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

805
01:00:38,006 --> 01:00:40,006
You go on now.

806
01:00:40,884 --> 01:00:42,884
You're free.

807
01:00:43,678 --> 01:00:45,678
You're free.

808
01:01:04,241 --> 01:01:06,241
Good luck, Brooksie.

809
01:01:43,905 --> 01:01:45,557
Dear fellas:

810
01:01:45,657 --> 01:01:49,992
I can't believe how fast things move
on the outside.

811
01:01:51,162 --> 01:01:54,477
Watch it, old-timer!
Want to get killed?

812
01:01:55,083 --> 01:01:58,738
I saw an automobile once
when I was a kid...

813
01:01:59,212 --> 01:02:01,762
...but now they're everywhere.

814
01:02:05,302 --> 01:02:09,639
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

815
01:02:25,447 --> 01:02:29,392
The parole board
got me into this halfway house...

816
01:02:29,492 --> 01:02:31,269
...called "The Brewer"...

817
01:02:31,369 --> 01:02:32,646
...and a job...

818
01:02:32,746 --> 01:02:35,891
...bagging groceries at the Food-Way.

819
01:02:37,250 --> 01:02:39,778
It's hard work and I try to keep up...

820
01:02:39,878 --> 01:02:42,447
...but my hands hurt most of the time.

821
01:02:42,547 --> 01:02:44,616
Make sure your man double-bags.

822
01:02:44,716 --> 01:02:47,327
Last time, the bottom near came out.

823
01:02:47,427 --> 01:02:50,455
Make sure you double-bag
like the lady says. Understand?

824
01:02:50,555 --> 01:02:52,040
Yes, sir. Surely will.

825
01:02:52,140 --> 01:02:56,390
I don't think the store manager
likes me very much.

826
01:02:58,688 --> 01:03:03,301
Sometimes after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

827
01:03:03,401 --> 01:03:05,053
I keep thinking...

828
01:03:05,153 --> 01:03:08,638
...Jake might just show up and say hello.

829
01:03:09,074 --> 01:03:11,076
But he never does.

830
01:03:12,285 --> 01:03:17,555
I hope, wherever he is, he's doing okay
and making new friends.

831
01:03:20,752 --> 01:03:23,557
I have trouble sleeping at night.

832
01:03:23,797 --> 01:03:27,050
I have bad dreams like I'm falling.

833
01:03:27,342 --> 01:03:29,553
I wake up scared.

834
01:03:29,761 --> 01:03:34,181
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

835
01:03:35,517 --> 01:03:40,630
Maybe I should get a gun and rob
the Food-Way so they'd send me home.

836
01:03:40,730 --> 01:03:46,255
I could shoot the manager while
I was at it. Sort of like a bonus.

837
01:03:46,736 --> 01:03:50,849
I guess I'm too old
for that sort of nonsense anymore.

838
01:03:50,949 --> 01:03:52,809
I don't like it here.

839
01:03:52,909 --> 01:03:57,499
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.
I've decided...

840
01:03:57,747 --> 01:03:59,747
...not to stay.

841
01:04:10,302 --> 01:04:12,996
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss...

842
01:04:13,096 --> 01:04:16,558
...not for an old crook like me.

843
01:05:19,037 --> 01:05:24,234
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss,
not for an old crook like me.

844
01:05:24,334 --> 01:05:28,280
P.S. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

845
01:05:28,380 --> 01:05:30,715
No hard feelings. Brooks. "

846
01:05:41,184 --> 01:05:43,564
He should have died in here.

847
01:05:48,692 --> 01:05:50,218
What the fuck have you done?

848
01:05:50,318 --> 01:05:53,633
It's a goddamn mess,
I'll tell you that.

849
01:05:58,535 --> 01:06:03,295
- What's all this?
- You tell me. They're addressed to you.

850
01:06:03,540 --> 01:06:05,540
Take it.

851
01:06:13,383 --> 01:06:15,383
"Dear Mr. Dufresne:

852
01:06:16,052 --> 01:06:18,121
In response to your inquiries...

853
01:06:18,221 --> 01:06:23,126
...the state has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project. "

854
01:06:23,226 --> 01:06:25,226
This is $200.

855
01:06:25,270 --> 01:06:29,382
"In addition, the library district
has generously responded...

856
01:06:29,482 --> 01:06:32,135
...with a donation of used books
and sundries.

857
01:06:32,235 --> 01:06:36,473
We trust this will fill your needs.
We now consider the matter closed.

858
01:06:36,573 --> 01:06:38,517
Please stop sending us letters. "

859
01:06:38,617 --> 01:06:41,436
Clear all this out
before the warden gets back.

860
01:06:41,536 --> 01:06:43,536
Yes, sir.

861
01:06:46,958 --> 01:06:48,958
Good for you, Andy.

862
01:06:51,087 --> 01:06:53,087
Wow!

863
01:06:53,423 --> 01:06:55,423
It only took six years.

864
01:06:56,927 --> 01:06:59,788
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week instead of one.

865
01:06:59,888 --> 01:07:03,375
I believe you're crazy enough.
Get this stuff out...

866
01:07:03,475 --> 01:07:04,418
...like he said.

867
01:07:04,518 --> 01:07:06,002
I've got to pinch a loaf.

868
01:07:06,102 --> 01:07:07,671
When I come back...

869
01:07:07,771 --> 01:07:10,406
...this is all gone, all right?

870
01:07:58,321 --> 01:08:00,321
Do you hear that?

871
01:09:08,433 --> 01:09:10,433
Dufresne!

872
01:09:12,145 --> 01:09:14,145
Andy, let me out!

873
01:09:20,570 --> 01:09:25,684
I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.

874
01:09:25,784 --> 01:09:28,145
Truth is, I don't want to know.

875
01:09:28,245 --> 01:09:31,050
Some things are best left unsaid.

876
01:09:34,292 --> 01:09:37,154
I like to think it was something
so beautiful...

877
01:09:37,254 --> 01:09:39,489
...it can't be expressed in words...

878
01:09:39,589 --> 01:09:43,244
...and makes your heart ache because of it.

879
01:09:44,135 --> 01:09:46,830
I tell you, those voices soared...

880
01:09:46,930 --> 01:09:51,334
...higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.

881
01:09:51,434 --> 01:09:54,880
It was like a beautiful bird
flapped into our drab cage...

882
01:09:54,980 --> 01:09:58,091
...and made those walls dissolve away.

883
01:09:58,191 --> 01:10:00,510
And for the briefest of moments...

884
01:10:00,610 --> 01:10:04,095
...every last man at Shawshank felt free.

885
01:10:06,157 --> 01:10:09,642
It pissed the warden off something awful.

886
01:10:10,120 --> 01:10:12,120
Open the door.

887
01:10:14,040 --> 01:10:16,040
Open it up!

888
01:10:17,127 --> 01:10:19,838
Dufresne, open this door!

889
01:10:21,173 --> 01:10:23,173
Turn that off!

890
01:10:29,472 --> 01:10:32,192
I am warning you. Turn that off!

891
01:10:49,659 --> 01:10:51,659
You're mine now.

892
01:10:58,627 --> 01:11:01,947
Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

893
01:11:02,047 --> 01:11:04,047
On your feet.

894
01:11:04,841 --> 01:11:07,476
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

895
01:11:09,012 --> 01:11:12,916
You couldn't play something good, huh?
Like Hank Williams?

896
01:11:13,016 --> 01:11:15,919
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

897
01:11:16,019 --> 01:11:19,256
- Was it worth two weeks?
- Easiest time I ever did.

898
01:11:19,356 --> 01:11:23,635
- No such thing as easy time in the hole.
- A week in the hole is like a year.

899
01:11:23,735 --> 01:11:27,139
- Damn straight.
- I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

900
01:11:27,239 --> 01:11:31,914
So they let you tote
that record player down there, huh?

901
01:11:32,661 --> 01:11:34,661
It was in here.

902
01:11:34,871 --> 01:11:36,871
In here.

903
01:11:37,207 --> 01:11:39,443
That's the beauty of music. They...

904
01:11:39,543 --> 01:11:41,878
...can't get that from you.

905
01:11:45,382 --> 01:11:49,037
Haven't you ever felt that way about music?

906
01:11:49,553 --> 01:11:53,633
Well, I played a mean harmonica
as a younger man.

907
01:11:53,723 --> 01:11:55,542
Lost interest in it, though.

908
01:11:55,642 --> 01:11:57,461
Didn't make much sense in here.

909
01:11:57,561 --> 01:12:00,005
Here's where it makes the most sense.

910
01:12:00,105 --> 01:12:02,632
You need it so you don't forget.

911
01:12:02,732 --> 01:12:04,217
Forget?

912
01:12:04,317 --> 01:12:07,404
Forget that there are...

913
01:12:07,612 --> 01:12:09,473
...places...

914
01:12:09,573 --> 01:12:13,483
...in the world that aren't made out of stone.

915
01:12:14,411 --> 01:12:16,146
There's something...

916
01:12:16,246 --> 01:12:17,814
...inside...

917
01:12:17,914 --> 01:12:19,983
...that they can't get to...

918
01:12:20,083 --> 01:12:21,860
...that they can't touch.

919
01:12:21,960 --> 01:12:23,960
That's yours.

920
01:12:24,921 --> 01:12:27,216
What are you talking about?

921
01:12:27,591 --> 01:12:29,591
Hope.

922
01:12:29,885 --> 01:12:31,885
Hope.

923
01:12:33,138 --> 01:12:35,832
Let me tell you something, my friend.

924
01:12:35,932 --> 01:12:38,268
Hope is a dangerous thing.

925
01:12:39,436 --> 01:12:41,816
Hope can drive a man insane.

926
01:12:42,480 --> 01:12:44,716
It's got no use on the inside.

927
01:12:44,816 --> 01:12:47,791
You'd better get used to that idea.

928
01:12:49,529 --> 01:12:51,529
Like Brooks did?

929
01:13:16,389 --> 01:13:18,389
Sit down.

930
01:13:22,729 --> 01:13:27,092
Says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

931
01:13:27,192 --> 01:13:29,386
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

932
01:13:29,486 --> 01:13:31,486
Oh, yes, sir.

933
01:13:31,988 --> 01:13:33,988
Without a doubt.

934
01:13:34,491 --> 01:13:37,636
I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

935
01:13:38,870 --> 01:13:41,080
No danger to society here.

936
01:13:41,331 --> 01:13:43,331
God's honest truth.

937
01:13:45,460 --> 01:13:47,585
Absolutely rehabilitated.

938
01:13:57,556 --> 01:13:59,556
Thirty years.

939
01:14:00,851 --> 01:14:03,503
Jesus, when you say it like that...

940
01:14:03,603 --> 01:14:05,728
You wonder where it went.

941
01:14:07,858 --> 01:14:10,408
I wonder where 10 years went.

942
01:14:14,990 --> 01:14:16,349
Here.

943
01:14:16,449 --> 01:14:19,339
A little parole rejection present.

944
01:14:20,453 --> 01:14:22,453
Go ahead and open it.

945
01:14:23,290 --> 01:14:25,400
Went through one of your competitors.

946
01:14:25,500 --> 01:14:29,835
I hope you don't mind.
I wanted it to be a surprise.

947
01:14:38,680 --> 01:14:40,680
It's very pretty.

948
01:14:41,892 --> 01:14:43,892
Thank you.

949
01:14:45,645 --> 01:14:47,645
You going to play it?

950
01:14:51,693 --> 01:14:53,693
No.

951
01:14:56,573 --> 01:14:58,573
Not right now.

952
01:15:15,675 --> 01:15:17,675
Roll in!

953
01:15:52,963 --> 01:15:54,963
Lights out!

954
01:16:28,790 --> 01:16:31,255
Andy was as good as his word.

955
01:16:31,293 --> 01:16:34,948
He wrote two letters a week instead of one.

956
01:16:36,131 --> 01:16:40,368
In 1959, the state senate
finally clued in to the fact...

957
01:16:40,468 --> 01:16:43,705
...they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

958
01:16:43,805 --> 01:16:48,210
Appropriations Committee
voted an annual payment of $500...

959
01:16:48,310 --> 01:16:50,310
...just to shut him up.

960
01:16:50,437 --> 01:16:53,507
And you'd be amazed how far
Andy could stretch it.

961
01:16:53,607 --> 01:16:56,676
He made deals with book clubs,
charity groups.

962
01:16:56,776 --> 01:16:59,930
He bought remaindered books
by the pound...

963
01:17:00,030 --> 01:17:02,030
Treasure Island.

964
01:17:02,115 --> 01:17:03,517
Robert Louis-

965
01:17:03,617 --> 01:17:04,768
Stevenson.

966
01:17:04,868 --> 01:17:06,868
Fiction, adventure.

967
01:17:08,788 --> 01:17:09,940
What's next?

968
01:17:10,040 --> 01:17:13,084
I got here Auto Repair...

969
01:17:13,835 --> 01:17:15,112
...and Soap Carving.

970
01:17:15,212 --> 01:17:18,532
Trade skills and hobbies.
Under "Educational," behind you.

971
01:17:18,632 --> 01:17:20,632
Count of Monte Crisco.

972
01:17:20,967 --> 01:17:23,517
That's "Crest," you dumb shit.

973
01:17:24,387 --> 01:17:25,747
By Alexandree...

974
01:17:25,847 --> 01:17:27,374
...Dum-ass.

975
01:17:27,474 --> 01:17:29,474
Dumb ass.

976
01:17:30,810 --> 01:17:32,810
Dumb ass?

977
01:17:34,773 --> 01:17:37,323
Dumas. Know what that's about?

978
01:17:38,985 --> 01:17:41,054
You'd like it.
It's about a prison break.

979
01:17:41,154 --> 01:17:45,851
We ought to file that
under "Educational" too, oughtn't we?

980
01:17:45,951 --> 01:17:50,522
The rest of us did our best
to pitch in when and where we could.

981
01:17:50,622 --> 01:17:52,524
By the year Kennedy was shot...

982
01:17:52,624 --> 01:17:57,320
...Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of turpentine...

983
01:17:57,420 --> 01:18:01,116
...into the best prison library
in New England...

984
01:18:01,216 --> 01:18:05,466
...complete with a fine selection
of Hank Williams.

985
01:18:11,518 --> 01:18:13,587
That was also when Warden Norton...

986
01:18:13,687 --> 01:18:16,965
...instituted his famous
"Inside Out" program.

987
01:18:17,065 --> 01:18:19,259
You may remember reading about it.

988
01:18:19,359 --> 01:18:22,596
It made the papers
and got his picture in Look magazine.

989
01:18:22,696 --> 01:18:24,097
It's no free ride...

990
01:18:24,197 --> 01:18:27,517
.. but rather a genuine
progressive advance...

991
01:18:27,617 --> 01:18:30,353
...in corrections and rehabilitation.

992
01:18:30,453 --> 01:18:33,106
Our inmates, properly supervised...

993
01:18:33,206 --> 01:18:35,942
...will be put to work outside these walls...

994
01:18:36,042 --> 01:18:39,697
...performing all manner of public service.

995
01:18:39,880 --> 01:18:42,199
These men can learn the value...

996
01:18:42,299 --> 01:18:46,203
...of an honest day's labor and
provide a service to the community...

997
01:18:46,303 --> 01:18:51,333
...at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q. Taxpayer.

998
01:18:51,433 --> 01:18:53,877
Of course he didn't tell the press...

999
01:18:53,977 --> 01:18:57,547
...that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1000
01:18:57,647 --> 01:19:00,801
There are 100 different ways
to skim off the top.

1001
01:19:00,901 --> 01:19:03,361
Men, materials, you name it.

1002
01:19:03,737 --> 01:19:06,723
And oh, my Lord,
how the money rolled in!

1003
01:19:06,823 --> 01:19:09,476
At this rate,
you'll put me out of business.

1004
01:19:09,576 --> 01:19:14,481
With this pool of slave labor,
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1005
01:19:14,581 --> 01:19:17,651
We're providing
a valuable community service.

1006
01:19:17,751 --> 01:19:22,596
That's fine for the papers,
but I've got a family to feed.

1007
01:19:24,090 --> 01:19:26,090
We go back a long way.

1008
01:19:26,927 --> 01:19:32,666
I need this highway contract. I don't
get it and I go under. That's a fact.

1009
01:19:32,766 --> 01:19:34,668
You have some of this fine pie...

1010
01:19:34,768 --> 01:19:38,763
...my missus made for you.
You think about that.

1011
01:19:46,404 --> 01:19:49,224
I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1012
01:19:49,324 --> 01:19:52,809
I already got my boys
committed elsewhere.

1013
01:19:54,371 --> 01:19:58,281
You be sure and thank Maisie
for this fine pie.

1014
01:19:58,542 --> 01:20:00,944
And behind every shady deal...

1015
01:20:01,044 --> 01:20:03,764
...behind every dollar earned...

1016
01:20:03,964 --> 01:20:07,109
...there was Andy, keeping the books.

1017
01:20:07,425 --> 01:20:08,827
Two deposits.

1018
01:20:08,927 --> 01:20:14,367
Maine National and New England First.
Night drops as always, sir.

1019
